<h1>Retention</h1>
<%- if @policy.nil? || @policy.empty? -%>
<p class="muted">No retention policy configured — backups are kept forever.
Set <span class="mono">retention:</span> in your config to enable pruning.</p>
<%- else -%>
<h2>Policy</h2>
<table>
  <tr><%- @policy.each_key do |key| -%><th><%= h(key) %></th><%- end -%></tr>
  <tr><%- @policy.each_value do |value| -%><td><%= h(value) %></td><%- end -%></tr>
</table>

<h2>Next prune would delete</h2>
<%- if @preview.deletions.empty? -%>
<%= notice("Nothing — every backup is within the retention policy.", kind: :ok) %>
<%- else -%>
<table>
  <tr><th>Destination</th><th>Database</th><th>Backup</th><th>Size</th></tr>
  <%- @preview.deletions.each do |del| -%>
  <tr>
    <td class="mono"><%= h(del.destination) %></td>
    <td><%= h(del.database) %></td>
    <td class="mono"><%= h(del.label) %></td>
    <td><%= h(human_size(del.size_bytes)) %></td>
  </tr>
  <%- end -%>
</table>
<p class="muted"><%= @preview.count %> backup set(s), <%= h(human_size(@preview.total_bytes)) %> total.
This is a preview — run the prune from the <a href="/actions">actions</a> page (or
<span class="mono">pgkeeper prune --apply</span>) to delete. Safety rails always apply:
the newest backup, the last verified backup, and anything newer than it are never deleted.</p>
<%- end -%>
<%- end -%>
